animal.description:
Why hello there! My name is Sophie.  I have a lot of great features that make ME FAB-U-LOUS!! I am calm, I pay no attention to the cats I live with, I’m okay with other dogs, I do great in the car and I have beautiful big brown eyes.  In fact, I am fully potty trained…would you believe have not had one accident while in rescues care???  I know sit and take treats extremely gently.  If people are petting me and they stop I will nudge them with my paw to let them know they need to continue with those pets!  My favorite activity is to eat.  I don’t understand why my foster parents can’t prepare breakfast or dinner any faster! I dance, I hop and I spin when I know my food is coming.  I love to get food from my wobbler and puzzle.  I have been to the family barn and enjoyed seeing all the interesting animals there.  I have also met other dogs and I pay them no attention.  My foster parents say that I do excellent on a leash too…I do not pull.  When they stop walking I then stop walking too-when they start walking again I do as well. 

Although I love to eat it is also my downfall.  We all have a downfall or two right??  I need to lose weight to help me with my legs and be in overall better health.  You see I’m an older girl (8) and my joints are stiff with arthritis and an old ACL tear…..so I’m a bit slower and had some trouble walking. But don’t worry!! I am on anti-inflammatory and pain medication- my walking has improved greatly.  I get short walks throughout the day and get 1 longer walk.  I am getting better with wrinkle & tail pocket cleanings, and ear medication but I still need work….sometimes I will run away from my foster parents.  I came into rescue with two severely infected ears.  After getting a culture and proper treatment my ears are doing much better however they will need life long care & maintenance.

Sophie's Adoption Fee is $450

If you would like to donate to Sophie's care, please go to our website at http://shopcebr.com/products/donation.


HOW TO QUALIFY FOR A CEBR BULLY To determine if you qualify to adopt one of our adorable bullies start by viewing our Adoption Area Map. If you fall within the boundaries and are interested in our bullies the first step is to complete an application by visiting www.ebullymatch.com

animal.description:
Welcome Ody to Little Black Dog Rescue!  Ody was found as a stray in Texas by a lovely woman who saved him from being hit by a car.  At approximately 4 years old, Ody is sweet and gentle but ready to play!  Ody is a gorgeous red and white hound-mix.  He is a happy, smiley boy in spite of his rough start in life. Ody has completed his heart worm treatment and heads north 1/30!

Please note: Little Black Dog Rescue is a FOSTER BASED rescue based in Fairfield County, Connecticut. We do NOT have a facility where you can come meet the dogs. We do adoption events every few months but primarily work one-on-one with each applicant to match the right dog to the right family. Once your application is received, all questions can be answered. We currently adopt to homes along the East Coast of the United States.  The adoption fee ranges from $250-$525 depending on age of the dog and transport distance/cost.

Please go to our website at www.littleblackdogrescue.org to see more information and to fill out our online application. Applications are required before conversations about potential matches can begin. Please check our website for up to date availability.

We are a non-profit organization and the adoption fee goes towards the transport, vetting, spay/neuter and boarding needs of the dogs we rescue. LBDR is a small rescue that receives a minor discount on vetting unlike larger rescues who self-administer or receive volume discounts. LBDR focuses on the rescue, care and placement of black dogs who are in danger of euthanasia due to their color, as well as other dogs who are in immediate need. LBDR is funded by donations which are used solely for the care of our dogs.

animal.description:
Gracie is about 7 years old, 60 lbs

She has a tragic story. her owner committed suicide in front of her. when the police came, she was guarding the body. cop shot her in the left front leg, completely shattering it. we took her to UGA to try to save the leg but could not.
She is now in a foster home

Gracie is a very sweet licky waggy friendly dog. She is a people person dog and far more interested in humans than other dogs. She gets on with other dogs, both male and female after proper introductions and she sticks very close to her human and is far more interested in following them around and being as close as she can rather than in what other dogs are doing. She is housetrained and very much recovered from her amputation as she shows no signs of distress and has adapted well to life as a tripod. She has the cutest piggy snores when she is comfortable and is crate trained. Gracie is a very snuggly dog who is happy to be your best friend and would like to come home with you and stay furever.

animal.description:
Dancer came to us from a shelter, and we do not know much about her past. She is very shy and nervous but she has made progress in overcoming her fears. We were told that she is a chihauhau mix. Prior to being groomed Dancer had long wirey hair, so we assume part of her mix is terrior. She is approximately 9 years old. She is a tall slender girl, standing 14 inches at her shoulder. She weighs about 12 lbs. She is somewhat thin and could stand to gain some weight so we are working on that. Dancer gets along well with other dogs. She seems to be getting the hang of potty training, and does well if taken out often. She is very unsure of herself on the leash so will need lots of work on that. As her confidence increases she will feel more comfortable on the leash. Dancer would benefit from another dog in the house, as she lacks confidence and feels more confident with another dog. Her new family will need to be patient with her as she learns to trust. She loves to have a massage (who doesn't?) and have her ears and neck scratched. She is starting to get excited when her foster mom returns home from being gone,...and two days ago while she was getting her ears scratched she laid down on the floor and rolled over for a belly rub! 

The requirements for Dancer are: (No Exceptions)


	A fenced in yard yard, as she startles easily and is a flight risk without a fence. 
	A quiet home with no small children. 


Dancer is spayed, has had her dental appointment, is heartworm negative, and up to date on her shots. Her adoption fee is $250.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

** Rory and Lorelai are a bonded pair and must be adopted together **

Lorelai is a 2 year old Belgian shepherd mix and an absolute lovebug! Rory and Lorelai were both surrendered to a Texas shelter and are completed devoted to each other. Where one goes, the other follows. Lorelai believes she is a lap dog and wants nothing more than to give kisses, be with her people and of course hanging out with Rory!

Rory and Lorelai have done well around other dogs and older kids. At just 2 years old, Lorelai has great energy and loves nothing more than to run and play till her heart's content. She and Rory love to be out in the yard running, playing, and having the best time! We are not sure that they are the best group for little, little people since they don't yet understand how easily their energy can overwhelm a small child. They may also knock over a little one with the crazy playing. However, an older child they can run and play with? Bring it on!

During the day while foster mom is away, they both hang out in their crates and recharge. As long as they are together, they are happy no matter what they are doing. They are both crate trained, and foster mom is working on some obedience training with them. As always, we recommend obedience training for all our rescues to bring out the best in them. With the Belgian shepherd mixes, there is always a good mix of stubborn thrown in with a hefty does of intelligence, so while training is more challenging, watching these girls bloom will be the best reward!

In the evening, after more afternoon play, Lorelai is excited to snuggle with foster mom on the couch. She loves getting chin scratches and gives kisses in return. Lorelai is a wonderfully affectionate dog and is working to make sure Rory knows everything is Ok.

Nuts and Bolts: 2 years old, 50lbs, spayed, good with dogs and older kids, no cats or birds due to Rory's high prey drive, crate trained, potty trained, some obedience training, needs a yard to run.

Rory and Lorelai are being fostered in Christiansburg, VA and would love to meet you!

If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

Yukon Jack is a young Alaskan Malamute who loves people but needs someone to give him the proper direction in life. Due to Jack exhibiting some resource guarding issues, especially with balls and other round objects, Jack needs some training and a breed experienced owner. He should not live with children. "Jack" gets along with both small and medium sized dogs as well as cats. Jack knows sit, stay, speak and down. Jack likes to go for short walks, play in the water and would be the very best lifelong adventure buddy someone can have!! Jack's version of running is a bit ridiculous, he loves to hop like a bunny around the yard, then run a little bit, then goes back to hopping! It is adorable. Jack is a calm, sweet, affectionate, young man!! Jack wants to please his people! Meet Yukon Jack today!!

animal.description:
***COVID 19 NOVEMBER 2020 PROTOCOL***

Due to the surge of Covid 19 and statewide restrictions, we are adopting to LOCAL (CLALLAM AND JEFFERSON COUNTY) RESIDENTS ONLY. We are not doing adoptions to Canada at this time due to the border closure. We do not ship animals. 

OPHS is appointment only. All potential adopters must fill out an adoption application prior to setting up an appointment to meet the animal. An application can be found on our website  https://www.ophumanesociety.org/dog-adoption-application

We have limited staff during this time, please allow 3-5 business days for us to process your application. We are screening the applications for the first BEST fit for each animal. 

If you are approved, you will be contacted by us via phone or email to schedule an appointment.

NAME: Luna
AGE: About 1 year
WEIGHT: About 50 lbs
BREED(S): Border Collie and Lab mix
REASON FOR ARRIVAL: Owner surrender

GENERAL INFO ABOUT PERSONALITY: Luna is a young and energetic girl who is eager to please and ready to learn.

She has lots of working dog energy paired with just being young. She would make an excellent hiking or running companion and overall adventure buddy. Luna's all time favorite game is playing fetch and she knows how to drop the ball pretty well! 

Luna has lived with another young dog and they got along well but would get themselves into trouble by finding ways to escape from their yard. She will need a securely fenced yard as well as someone who will not leave her outside unattended. If she doesn't get enough exercise and training in her new home, she will likely revert back to her bad habits.

Around other dogs, Luna can be somewhat possessive over her toys/ball. Additionally, Luna has shown us reactivity on leash when meeting other dogs and therefore might not be a good fit around every dog. Luna should not be around cats or other small critters. Don't let this sway you though, in the right hands Luna is a sweet girl who really wants to please her people!

Activity Level? High
Training Needs? High
House Trained? Yes
Leash Trained? Yes 
Comfortable with kids? Supposedly
Comfortable with strangers? Yes
History with other dogs? Has lived with sibling dog but would be best as only pet. 
History with cats? Not good

Additional MEDICAL notes: None
Additional BEHAVIOR notes: None

ADOPTION FEE: $150 for an adult dog.

Adoption fee includes: Spay/neuter, initial vaccines, a microchip, rabies vaccine when appropriate, and one free veterinary visit with a local participating clinic.

animal.description: Roofus is a handsome 3-year-old mixed-breed fellow who currently weighs about 63 pounds. He came to SFAS when his previous guardian could no longer care for him and he is now ready for another loving family. Here at the shelter, Roofus has been excited to meet new people, has some of the best zoomies around and is always ready to play. He is very outgoing and full of energy. If you have another dog at home feel free to bring them for a meet N greet during your appointment. Roofus's adoption fee is $130 He is neutered and microchipped and has age-appropriate vaccinations. A licensing/microchip fee may apply. To meet Roofus or to be added to his waitlist, call (505) 983-4309 x 1610 and leave a voicemail message that includes the DOG'S NAME, plus YOUR NAME and A PHONE NUMBER - OR e-mail this information to adoption@sfhumanesociety.org. A scheduler will call you back within 48 hours to confirm your request. If you have other dogs at home, tell the scheduler you would like to bring them along for a Meet n' Greet. SFAS offers a variety of excellent training classes, seminars and Trainer Talks led by animal behavior professionals. These are half-price for animals adopted from any shelter or rescue group! Due to current COVID-19 restrictions, classes and talks are all presented virtually using Zoom. For course descriptions, schedules and registration, visit https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/group-training-classes/ for classes and https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/special-seminars-and-workshops/ for seminars and Trainer Talks.

animal.description:
Soren is a 6-mo-old cattle dog mix, currently weighing around 30 pounds. He was found living in a culvert on the Navajo Nation near a kind human who discovered him and took him in for a few days until he found his way to Blackhat Humane Society.  

Soren has quickly adjusted to living indoors and loves his foster mom. He is in crate training and is doing well learning to walk on a leash. This little boy is very sweet and is very tuned-in to people and pets around him. He is a character and loves playing with other dogs and is able to entertain himself with toys. Soren is almost cat-like. He loves being loved on and is learning the difference between loving and playing. Soren is fiercely protective and very trainable and like any pup will be an extraordinarily wonderful pet for a family who will continue his training and help him to reach his full potential. ..and, he is a already a great travel companion!

This boy is being fostered in Ganado, Arizona. For more information or to meet this special sweetheart, contact Lavonne at lyjuhl@yahoo.com.

Also submit an online application at blackhathumanesociety.org.

animal.description:
Flip Flop is a 1-year old dingus who is looking for an active adult home.    He’s very keyed up at the shelter, so it’s hard for him to settle down and nail his first impressions.  He’s a sweet kiddo and has done well outside the shelter in his foster home.  His foster writes:
He is SUCH a sweet and curious boy, wanting to be anywhere we are in the house. There isn’t a mean bone in his body. He loves to snuggle and isn’t shy about laying on top of us when given the chance! Flip Flop loves toys of all kinds- chews, plush, balls, challenge toys and he will entertain himself with toys or respond well to being played with. We limited toys out in the house to 2 as he likes to collect them for himself. He likes to playfully growl and play tug of war. Flip Flop does fine being bathed in an enclosed space as he will try to get out otherwise, and he loves running around in the yard. 
He does sometimes nibble on various items (blankets, pillows) but responds easily to redirects to dog-approved items. Other than the first day at our house, Flip Flop has only gone potty outside and even has rung the bells on the door a few times to indicate going outside. He sleeps through the night in his crate without any problems at all and barks in the morning when ready to wake up! He has taken to the crate really well if needed when being left alone- No destructive behavior noted at all. He is not well leash trained and pulls heavily on a leash, but Gentle Leader head collar training is starting, as he responded well (other than trying to get it off :)) when we practiced it with our current dog’s Gentle Leader. 
He follows commands for sit, lay down, and no and usually responds to his name. He does not respond to come, down/off. “

animal.description:
Meet siblings Kara, Sasha & Neron.

They are around 4 1/2 months old Labrador Retriever & Italian Greyhound possible mixes. with gorgeous brindle coats. The 2 female are brindle.

They were rescued from a flea market - someone abandoned them there - they were weak and with mange; and now they have completed their wellness program and the 3 of them are doing very well and fully recovered.

They will be medium sizes once full grown.

As with all rescued fury kids; they are going to need training, love reinforcement; as you know they all come from a tough beginning on their lives and the art of adopting a rescued creature is to bring them to be the best they can be with love and patience.

Their adoption fee includes being spayed/neutered, they have received their 3 core puppy vaccines, dewormed, and a free health check up through a local participating vet clinic.

Single young German Shepherd seeking loving family to move in with. Not looking for a room to rent, I want to share your home. I will be very faithful and loving. I love to chase the spray from the water hose. The final bonus is that I won't clear your coffee table with my tail because I had to have it amputated after I was hurt. I have a big bark, I'm sure it will scare bad guys away. I am still a little wild and crazy, my rescue peeps said they will work on my manners while I am waiting for my new family. P. S. Please tell that nice photographer lady that I wasn't trying to be mean. I just wasn't sure what that thing was that she pointed at me I met a cat, I'm not quite sure what to think about it, maybe cats are OK.

I'm also not skeered to go outside in the rain.

I have a special talent, I am a wound detector. One of my foster sisters had a boo boo and I kept licking her wound until her hooman investigated and found the sore. Does that make me Dr. Dog?

Anyway, I still need some work on manners but if you take me home we can work on that together.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

** Rory and Lorelai are a bonded pair and must be adopted together **

Rory is a 1 year old Belgian shepherd mix and this girl is ready to explore! Rory and Lorelai were both surrendered to a Texas shelter and are completed devoted to each other. Where one goes, the other follows. Rory is the more timid of the pair until she gets to know you.

Rory and Lorelai have done well around other dogs and older kids. At just 1 year old, Rory has great energy and loves nothing more than to run and play till her heart's content. She and Lorelai love to be out in the yard running, playing, and having the best time! We are not sure that they are the best group for little, little people since they don't yet understand how easily their energy can overwhelm a small child. They may also knock over a little one with the crazy playing. However, an older child they can run and play with? Bring it on!

During the day while foster mom is away, they both hang out in their crates and recharge. As long as they are together, they are happy no matter what they are doing. They are both crate trained, and foster mom is working on some obedience training with them. As always, we recommend obedience training for all our rescues to bring out the best in them. With the Belgian shepherd mixes, there is always a good mix of stubborn thrown in with a hefty does of intelligence, so while training is more challenging, watching these girls bloom will be the best reward!

In the evening, after more afternoon play, Rory loves to lay in her dog bed and watch the household. If you get out of her line of sign, she loves to follow you around to see what interesting things you may be doing. While foster mom and Lorelai are snuggling on the couch, Rory has always thought her bed had the better view of the TV. As time goes on however, and she opens up more, Rory has started to venture on the couch as well. Each day she becomes more loving and open.

Nuts and Bolts: 1 year old, 50lbs, spayed, good with dogs and older kids, no cats or birds due to high prey drive, crate trained, potty trained, some obedience training, needs a yard to run.

Rory and Lorelai are being fostered in Christiansburg, VA and would love to meet you!

If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

animal.description:
lf you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire (http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/) and e-mail questions to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

Meet Cora! 

Cora is house trained. She is sweet and gentle and likes to cuddle. She has found snow to be a lot of fun. She is low key in the house, playing gently or just chilling with her people. She seems very smart and eager to learn new things.

She was recently returned to us as she turned out not to do well in a home with children. The noise and bustle made her a bit on edge! So a quiet home with predictable and little foot traffic is what we are looking for. She does not like meeting new people, and can often get defensive of her space in those situations. She is ok after gentle meetings, and when she is not pushed and given her own space. She does have some separation anxiety, but is working to improve that! 

This sweet girl was left at a Georgia shelter with her nine puppies but the then of them made their way to Homeward Trails via a private plane! She has been an attentive mom to her nine pups and now it's her turn for some attention. She is underweight at 40 lbs and we believe she should be closer to 55 lbs or so. She is good with people and other dogs, but is not a fan of cats!

 Walks well on leash for most days, or will run alongside of you if you like to run! She would make a great jogging buddy. 

Adoption Coordinator: Mary Beth 
Location: Foster
The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee DOES INCLUDE spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide a 30-minute phone consult with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert advice and guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program/

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Sedona began her life in a small town in northern AZ and was surrendered to a shelter there at 6 months old when her owners realized she was too much dog for their household. Luckily for Sedona, the shelter worked hard to network her and she was welcomed in the Paw Placement family in Phoenix, where her chances of finding the perfect forever home quadrupled!

Sedona is a sweet and energetic young girl. She is a working breed and therefore is highly intelligent and high energy. She is playful with her doggy foster siblings of all sizes, and would very much prefer to go home with a doggy playmate or two. Sedona has adjusted to city life well, however, she will not do well in a low activity household - she needs to run and play, hike and walk, and use her noggin to learn new skills and tricks. Sedona is crate and house trained in her foster home. She is not appropriate for an apartment type setting, she requires a house with a yard.

Sedona has become best friends with her foster brother, Beckham, who is also adoptable. These two really balance each other's energies; they spend equal time running, romping, playing and snoozing or chewing antlers. If you're looking for two intelligent, energetic dogs, they might just be the pair for you!

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an adoption application. Because we expect a large number of applications, and are still understaffed due to COVID19, we will only be able to email those applicants that are approved to schedule a meet and greet. Thank you in advance for your understanding if you don't hear back from us regarding your application.

animal.description:
Hello There!!! My name is Sheila-Belle and I am a two year old silver female Siberian Husky.  I started out with a family that kept me confined inside a fenced yard with little to no attention or activity.  I eventually escaped and ended up in the dog pound where Best Friends of Baker found me and placed me in a foster home.  I am currently living in a home with two teenagers who walk me daily, and play with me in a large dog arena.  There is a very large and older female German Shepherd who is the matriarch of the dog arena.  She has taught me how to run, play, wrestle with her and other dogs without being aggressive or timid.  I have also met barn cats, large and small dogs at the boarding facility and we all get along.  There are horses and three goats, chickens and other farm animals that I could care less about.  I am a very friendly and loving dog who is looking for an physically active family with or without children.  Siberians need and enjoy a full physical workout daily to keep them happy and satisfied. I am a small built female, but fast and strong enough to pull a sled on snow or wheels, go for long runs or hikes or even a slow and leisurely walk around the neighborhood daily.  I am current on all my vaccinations, wormed, and micro-chipped.  I will be spayed prior to my adoption.  I do require a secure fenced yard where I can be safe and secure, yet have access to my family inside the house.  I do not want to spend my life isolated outside, I want to be with a loving family that will allow me to sleep on a bed inside where it is warm and I can see and feel the love from them.

If you would like to be considered for adoption, please submit an application https://www.bestfriendsofbaker.org/adoption-application and a volunteer will be in touch. Please understand we are an all-volunteer organization and we make every effort to return inquiries as soon as possible.

FAQ:
"is Fido available for adoption?"
Please assume that if a dog is listed as 'adoptable' on our Petfinder page we are still accepting applications for that pet. We do our best to keep the page up to date. 

"is Fido good with dogs/older cats/male cats/children/orangutans/vacuums?"
Each animal is different, and our profiles try to address these questions. If you do not find your answer in the pet's profile, please submit an application or inquiry and a volunteer will be happy to speak with you about a particular animal.

"what is the adoption process?"
You submit an application at: https://www.bestfriendsofbaker.org/adoption-application 
and then the applications for that animal are reviewed and references are checked. The home that is the best fit is contacted first if there are multiple applicants.  If there are homes of equal fit for the pet, the first submitted will be chosen. The chosen adopter will be contacted (usually by phone) and a meet-and-greet and or home visit is arranged to determine if the adoption will be finalized. If the person passes on the pet, we will contact the next applicant in line. 

"how much does it cost?"
Dog adoption fees generally range from $100.00-400.00 depending on how much veterinary care the dog has received. All adoption donations are tax-deductible and donations above the requested fee are appreciated. Every cent from our adoption fees goes toward helping the next animal in need. 

"what veterinary care has Fido received?"
Dogs are generally vetted upon intake and receive wormer and vaccines (rabies and a distemper/parvo combination vaccine). If intact and of the appropriate age, they are also spayed or neutered.  

Thank you for your interest in adopting. 

Best Friends of Baker, Inc.
P.O. Box 183
Baker City, OR 97814
541-519-7387

animal.description: Introducing Callie....A unbelievably sweet sweet girl, good with everything...LOVES, LOVES, LOVES everyone she meets...She must go to a home with another dog and preferably a cat as well...Having other animals around to play with makes her so happy...she goes to doggy daycare and gets excited everytime she goes...she never wants to leave lol.. She needs an active family that is willing to take her places and everywhere with them, as she goes stir crazy just staying in a house all day. She is very very eager to please and needs someone who is willing to work with her, as she is always looking at you to tell her what to do...she just wants to love you and make you happy...per the owner of the rescue ( who is the foster) she has personally fostered thousands of animals, but none have had her, like Callie does...shes a very very special girl, and is sooo incredibly smart and loving...she is still a puppy, so does like her shoes now and then lol...The foster is going to be very selective on where she goes and wants to make sure it is the right home for her and she has the family that she so deserves.

Courtesy Post: Bubba needs a home
This pup was found by this animal rescuer and his owner was never found. She named this nice pup, Bubba. He is extremely playful and looking for a home with someone that will make him part of the family. He has been trained to walk on a leash, too! Bubba is about 2 years old and a mix of lab, bully, and something with pointy ears. He weighs 75 lbs. He is now neutered, heartworm free, on heartworm prevention, up to date on his rabies shot, and dewormed. If you have any questions or would like to meet Bubba, please call Elaine at 864-378-6251.

This pup is posted as courtesy and is not affiliated with the Humane Society of McCormick County (HSMC). By courtesy posting, we are offering our website as an additional outlet to help an owner or rescuer gain additional exposure for the pup they are trying to place.

animal.description: Dee is a sweet, lanky rabbit who is so ready to find a soft place to land.  He is only 8 months, which means Dee is any open book, and the two of you can write his story together.  Dee came to us from one of our rescue partners in NE Georgia.  He is all puppy energy, and we’re negotiating not jumping up on us to say “hello, hello, hello, hello” while we walk together.  That’s a work in progress, but he has definitely settled down a little more, even with just a couple of weeks of practice.  With a little gentle guidance and some daily practice, you’re going to help Dee grow into the prince he is.  He would love to find a home where he can get daily walks and lots of play time.  He would love to learn how to plan fetch and learn some skills he could show off.  Dee seems friendly and curious about other dogs.  If you’re looking for a joyful, adventurous companion, he would be a great choice.  Because he’s still working on his manners, we recommend him for older children, maybe about 6 and older.

animal.description:
Bandit is a sweet old man who just wants to lay around and be loved. At 8 years old, all that running around is for the pups. He's more than happy to stay close to you and watch the kids have fun. Bandit weighs 45 pounds.
While his total history is a mystery, you can tell he's been in a few bad spots. The scars on his face are proof that he's had some run ins with some aggressive characters. But don't let his age fool you, he's no slouch. Him and one of my other dogs had a scuffle and Bandit will give it just as much as he can take it. He won't start anything, but he can hold his own if he needs to.
He gets along just fine with other dogs as long they don't mess with him first. I haven't had him around kids or cats, but I don't see any reason why they would bother him any. Very young children will probably need supervision as he gets anxious if his ears or tail is pulled. As long as you are respectful to him, he is respectful to you.
He's crate trained and housebroken. He can knows how to sit very well, and will basically stay put until you give him a reason to move. If you want a low energy dog to curl up on the couch with, he's your man!

animal.description:
Peaches currently lives with 2 adults and 2 cats. She gets a A+ for her cat interactions. Peaches is good with male dogs, but isn’t good with female dogs. 

She is 100% house trained and hasn’t had any accidents indoors. Peaches loves, and I mean loves to sleep as much as she can. She also enjoys her leisurely strolls and does well on the leash. In the time we’ve had her she’s met at least 10 adult people including a toddler and is friendly to everyone she meets. She doesn’t jump on people but will definitely smell them if they want to pet her. 

This dog is a 10/10 sweetheart and would be a loving, loyal dog to anyone. Peaches is also crate trained but I leave her out of the crate all day since usually one of us is home. If we are gone for less than 4 hours we leave her out of the crate during that time, too. For bedtime, I also leave her out of her crate. She will sleep all night and stay in bed late until you are ready to take her out to potty. She’s an older lazy dog that loves a good place to sleep and relax. Peaches is not very vocal, I’ve only heard her bark twice and that was because our cat scared her by jumping on the couch when she was sleeping. 

She knows how to sit and to wait. She also enjoys car rides and ice cream from DQ. Sometimes she plays with toys but she really prefers sleepy time. 

Peaches is 6 year old, affectionate gentle giant at 75-80 pounds* that is easy to fall in love with. 


*She is on a diet and ideally would be 70 pounds.

animal.description:
How I Arrived At NHS: I came from a shelter in Oklahoma. This animal came from a shelter located in Tulsa, Ok. Animal shelters in the south are overrun with animals. Northwoods takes dogs from a shelter where these dogs would otherwise be euthanized. They now will have a second chance here in Minnesota.

Notes from my foster parents:  Chico (who has no idea that's his name so it could really be changed to anything) has been wonderful! He's been in our home since 1/9 and has been incredibly well behaved.
He is an outdoor enthusiast! He has been loving the fresh snow and romps in the woods on a long lead. He benefits greatly from getting outside and burning off energy. He would stay outside as long as we let him, but does settle down nicely when back inside.
He truly loves people. Whether it's in his nature, having been in a shelter for awhile, or a combination of both, he does want to be with us constantly. So we've been working on teaching him it's ok to not be with us constantly but it's obviously been baby steps and short intervals of time.
He really doesn't like being closed into the kennel. At night we've been letting him sleep on a dog bed in our room and he's much more calm than when we tried the kennel for 2 nights. He lays down when we say goodnight and doesn't even move until we get up in the morning. I work from home and leave open the door to the kennel by my desk and he freely goes in there and sleeps during the day.
He's left everything alone in our house: shoes, mittens, pillows, hasn't tried to get into garbage cans or a bag of dog treats on the end table. He really has great manners!
When we eat dinner he doesn't beg or get too close. He lays down on a dog bed and doesn't even whine. He does really love his own mealtimes though and we've been using a slow down bowl that takes him 10 minutes to eat a meal. He would really do well continuing with a bowl like this or a food dispenser because he eats very fast.
He's a pretty tough chewer and does well with filled, frozen kongs. But he can't ignore a squeaky toy either! He loves destroying the squeaky.
We've figured out he knows a few basic commands: sit (but mostly with a hand signal and not so much the word), drop it, go lay down. We've been slowly working on clicker training and he stays very engaged and eager to learn.
He really is a great dog who will make a great family member. He's up for adventures and loves car rides, even falling asleep on straight stretches. And he's very loving and snuggly and would eagerly snuggle up on the couch with you. 

Notes from NHS volunteer: I walked and later played ball with Chico. He is a bundle of fun!  I think he has springs in his feet. He almost dances/bounces when you walk him. Then when you throw the ball he will chase it and sometimes bring it back, or not, but if I pick up the ball and raise my hand in the air, he automatically sits until I throw it. He also knows shake. I did notice that when we were walking in the woods, Chico was very alert to any little animal that he saw or heard in the woods. He would likely NOT be good with cats in the home.

Good With Kids: Unknown
Good With Cats: Unknown
Good With Dogs:  Unknown
We do require a meet-and-greet with your dog(s) onsite prior to any dog adoptions here at Northwoods.

All the dogs at Northwoods Humane Society have had a basic exam by a tech. They have been microchipped, tested for Heartworm (if over 6 months of age), had at least their first distemper combo vaccination (2nd if here longer), dewormed with a general dewormer, and had a flea and tick treatment applied if applicable. All the dogs will be spayed or neutered before they are adopted to their new permanent homes. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix.

We will provide all the supplies needed to foster. Please be a hero and foster! 

He weighs about 65 lbs and is now close to his healthy weight. He loves to nap on the couch, chew on his rubber bone, and romp around with with his foster brother at the park. Loves all dogs but best with dogs 30 lbs and over. Potty trained and crate trained. Plenty of slobber and snuggles to go around! 

Hef is a gentle giant. Foster described him as a Velcro boy, he loves to follow her around the house. He is the best napper in the world. Lots of slobber and love to share.

You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallasdogrrr.org. For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. animal.description:
Meet  Gizmo Giblet! 6 years old and 14lbs.
Gizmo should not be adopted into a home with kids as he prefers to be an only child. 
Gizmo is the dog for you if you’re looking for a boy that wants to be beside you, no matter what! You understand that he communicates by growling along with nasty comments, and you don’t mind that he will bark and scratch at doors to get your attention when you leave him. He will also help keep friends and family away by barking, growling and snapping at them when they get close to you. He is a happy and playful boy that loves squeak toys and will insist on sleeping beside you and may pee in your bed
 

Interested in becoming a forever home for Gizmo Giblets? Fill out our online adoption application: http://www.friendswithfourpaws.org/adoption-form.html This is the first step in our process, and we don't go any further without an application.

Find more adoptable pets, news and information on Instagram @friendswithfourpaws or our Facebook page Friends with Four Paws .

We put a lot of time and energy into processing our adoptions to find our babies the best fit home for them and you.  Please do not submit an application if you are not serious about adopting Gizmo Giblets.
We are so excited to work with you to find you a new forever friend, and Gizmo Giblets the perfect forever home, and appreciate you working with us.  
For immediate consideration, please attach your application to the initial inquiry to help us expedite the process.

Our adoption fee is $475. This includes their spay/neuter surgery, full (age appropriate) vaccinations, microchip insertion and registration, deworming, heartworm testing and prevention, flea and tick prevention and travel expenses.

All of our dogs are rescued from local shelters and the general public. Each dog is then placed in a foster home where he/she is kept for quarantine, to ensure if the dog gets sick it can receive proper treatment. We have foster homes in the NJ/NY area waiting to receive their fosters. Once an animal has received an application or there's an adopter interested, we make arrangements for transport. If a dog is already in foster care in NYC/NJ, an adopter will be put in touch with the foster home AFTER an application is being processed.

Thank you in advance for your patience with our process and for making adoption YOUR option!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.wagoninn.rescuegroups.org

*****Courtesy Post*****
This is Lulu. Lulu is a 45 lb, 4 year old boxer-hound-pit mix. She's an absolute sweetheart, but she wasn't socialized as a puppy: she was found in the woods at age 1 in terrible condition. We rescued her in 2017. She loves running and cuddling, and is in her own home generally a very sweet dog; but she's unable to be around most other dogs except those in our household and she exhibits signs of resource guarding aggression from her time in the woods.

We are looking to rehome her with someone who needs a sweet, loving, loyal, imperfect companion. She should live in a place where she can run and get lots of exercise, ideally without other animals (although she's great friends with both our dog and cat, she is usually wary of pets she doesn't know.) She needs a strong, patient owner, as she is small but mighty. We love her dearly and she would make a great pet in a no children, no pet (or certain pets) home. If you have any questions, please email newhomeforlulu@gmail.com

Additional important information: She should not be left alone outside in a fenced in yard unless it's very tall, she can hop our 6ft fence. She is currently on a medium dose of fluoxitine (at the recommendation of our vet) to help with her anxiety, and that would need to continue. She needs frequent walks and hikes. Any adopter would also have to continue to work patiently with her fear and resource guarding issues. We were doing our best managing her issues and planned to keep her because she is a tremendously loving and playful dog. However, she bit our toddler on the head when he reached for her chew toy in a resource guarding situation; it was not a serious bite, but the potential for more scenarios like this exist and we have a duty to protect our son while also ensuring Lulu isn't relegated to a life in a crate or tied outside anytime our son is around. She deserves more than to spend her life in a crate or to be euthanized by a shelter at such a young age though, and we really hope to find her a new home.

How to Adopt Me!

animal.description:
This is Miriam! She’s about 2 years old and short legged at 38 lbs. We think she’s a cattle dog/terrier mix. 

She was saved from death row and is now living the life. She loves other dogs and humans, but doesn’t feel too strongly about cats. Good with children but maybe better with older kids. Miriam needs a little time to warm up to new people sometimes, but once she does she LOVES you!

She’s is house-broken and kennel trained- but she loves sleeping in the bath tub haha or next to you! She also loooves the doggie pool!

She’s up to date on vaccinations, flea prevention and HW prevention. 

Miriam gets nervous when bad weather rolls around, but other than that she is very easygoing. She would make the perfect little dog for someone!

She loves to run and play, loves to be in your lap, hugs your legs, loves her Kong with PB, head rubs, and gives kisses when you hold or carry her. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
'Quiet as a mouse!' That's how Pippa's hosts described her when she stayed in a couple of temporary homes on her way from a GA shelter to her foster home in VA. Quiet as a mouse and not much bigger than one, 10-year-old Pippa had all but given up before New Rattitude pulled the tiny Rattie mix from the shelter. She had been picked up as a stray, malnourished, severely underweight, and barely able to walk without falling over. Over the past three months, Pippa has received plenty of TLC, including dental work and veterinary care, that has enabled her to reach a healthy weight of 9 1/2 lbs. Full of appreciation for the 'second life' she has been given, she wants to be a very special pup to a very special person, who can help her manage a few remaining physical issues. One of them is a condition much like acid reflux disease in people; it just has a much longer name--bilious vomiting syndrome. Fortunately it can be prevented by feeding her 3x/day at 8-hour intervals. Pippa may also have the beginning stages of intervertebral disc disease (IVDD), which will require a home environment where she doesn't have to manage stairs (especially uncarpeted ones) and slick floors. She would benefit from a single-story house with easy access to a fenced yard, gently paced leash walks, and a ramp for furniture so that she can avoid jumping. Fortunately she's not prohibited from playing with canine buddies because this girl LOVES other dogs, but to be safe, playtime should be gentle, supervised, and limited to similarly sized dogs. She doesn't regard cats with the same affection she has for dogs, but the dog-savvy kitty in her foster home is not the least bit fazed by her. Because of her tiny size and the need to avoid physical activity that might aggravate her IVDD, she should not live in a home with young children. One of the joys in having Miss Pippa around is observing how much pleasure she derives from simple things like rolling in the grass or curling up in a comfy dog bed. And while she's not too sure what plush toys are for, she's very happy to repurpose them as pillows. Pippa is completely house-trained and will signal (quietly, of course) when she needs to go out. In this time of staying home and enjoying small pleasures, one of the greatest small pleasures you can enjoy will come from adopting Pippa, who will love you unconditionally, follow you like a shadow, and be quiet as a mouse. See more photos of Pippa in her online album at https://imageevent.com/newrattitude/pippa .
Our adoption fee is $175 for adult dogs or $225 for puppies under 6 months old.

If you are interested in adopting this dog,
PLEASE READ THE DETAILED ADOPTION PROCESS information on our website
at www.
NewRattitude.org/adopt/

From there, you can access our adoption application or contact our Adoption Team for more info.

animal.description:
There has never been a dog more appropriately named because this dog is so Sweet! Sweetie has been through a lot in her 3 years, she was used as a breeding dog and dumped when she was no longer needed, the owner did not realize she was pregnant. While at the shelter, that litter was aborted and Sweetie was then put up for adoption, but no one was interested. Paws From Afar was notified about her impending death and we stepped up and pulled her. This was in February and she was stuck without a ride to get to us. 

Thank goodness for Dr. Kristy in Missouri who stepped in and offered to treat her heartworm and foster her until we could get her to New England.

Sweetie has finally arrived to us and is currently with our foster and trainer, Ms. Emily, in Maine. She is a very happy go lucky dog that loves other dogs, snuggling, going for walks and hikes.

She would do well in a home with kids, other dogs, NO CATS or other small animals, people with sofas, going on hikes, walks on the beach, you know active, BUT she is also mellow, very sweet and seeks attention.

animal.description:
Elsa is a stunning, 4-year-old, black & tan, female, German Shepherd Dog.  She arrived in rescue when her owner lost her home.  Elsa was raised by a single adult so we are looking for an adult only home for her.

Elsa has been around other dogs, but she isn’t inclined to play with other dogs.  We feel she would really love to be the only pet in her new household as she is very people-focused.

Elsa has been absolutely spoiled in her foster home.  She has been entertained with lots of playful brushing, dancing (yes, she can dance!), hide and seek, tennis ball play, her favorite snake and lots of massage. Yes, completely spoiled!

Elsa will flourish with time spent on basic commands and training.  She is well behaved, crate-trained and sleeps in her crate with the door open.  You will hear her happy in the house as she moans and sighs when she is relaxed.  It will take her a bit to adjust (as all shepherds do) and needs a special match!

Elsa is a very gentle dog to have around the house and she has impeccable house manners, too.  Although, she hides her edible dog bones all over the house - under the carpets and in the corners - super sweet & crumbly remembrances.

Elsa loves to be brushed daily and she likes different brushes.  She likes to watch and approve her food preparation, but has a sensitive stomach and needs a consistent diet.  Elsa would love someone who works from home,  or who is partially retired, or who has a flexible schedule; she has had no accidents and no anxiety issues.  She loves to go in the car and is a perfect angel; she will take over the driver's seat if you leave, though. ?

Elsa's new home will need to have a fenced or secured backyard, please.

If you would like to adopt Elsa, please visit our website and apply today!

https://www.washingtongsd.org/adopt

Please note that we require a secure fenced yard.

Our hours are by appointment only. IF WE FIND YOU TO BE A GOOD MATCH YOU WILL BE CONTACTED typically within 72 hours. YOU WILL HEAR FROM US ONLY IF WE FIND YOU TO BE A GOOD MATCH FOR ONE OF OUR RESCUE ANIMALS AND OUR ADOPTION GUIDELINES/PROGRAM. WE MUST REVIEW A COMPLETED APPLICATION BEFORE A POSSIBLE APPOINTMENT IS ARRANGED. NO EXCEPTIONS. All visits with the puppies/dogs are by approved applications and appointments only.

* We reserve the right to refuse any adoption without justification and not all applications or inquiries may receive a response. *

Thank you for your interest in our rescue dogs.

animal.description:
Meet Max - a super sweet wenior Schnauzer! He's 14 years young, bright eyed, and he's got a new lease on life!

We rescued Max from the shelter. He ended up there because his owners had passed away. He was not only heartbroken, he was also homeless. The future didn't look so bright for ol' Max.

It turns out Max, being a bit older, has a few conditions which are totally manageable with TLC and meds: arthritis, an enlarged heart , bladder stones (so he needs a special diet), a harmless fatty tumor under his front leg that we already had removed, and the poor old man has an enlarged prostate! He will need to be neutered at 14 years old!! 

Something about Max told us we shouldn't walk away and leave him there. His owners would have wanted him to live a good life after all. 

Despite his medical issues, Max is doing well for his age! He is a super sweet and a highly lovable dog. After a bit of grooming -- he now looks like a handsome brand spankin' new young dog! 

##### NOTES FROM HIS FOSTER: ##### Max loves to play fetch. Max is great on and off a leash. He enjoys walks around the neighborhood on a leash.Max is good with other dogs and cats so far. Max seems to be fabulous with all other people. Loves to be rubbed and scratched but he isn't a lap cuddler. Most of all, Max is just loveable and wants to be loved. He would be happy to go anywhere and everywhere with his forever person. Please come and visit me at the Adoption Center inside PetSmart in Midland, TX! 

Check out all the currently adoptable pets on www.midlandhumane.org/adoptables

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Hagan, and my New Year's Resolution for 2021 is to find a place I truly belong. So to do that, I decided to write down a few things you should know about me!
One word people use to describe me is ""sweet,"" and not to brag or anything, but I don't think they're wrong. Being this sweet comes with some big responsibilities, though! For starters, I have to be as polite as possible, and I try my best to do just that. I try to walk nicely for the volunteers, and I always make sure to smile at people as they pass by.
To make sure I don't get too excited, I like to run my energy out in the play yards. My favorite toys are the ones that squeak. Oh, I just love it when they make that noise! I love to play fetch with the toys, and I find that after a good long time outside, the one thing that really hits the spot is a belly rub.
So, if you get the chance, come say hello to me! I'm a little shy at first, but who isn't when they meet strangers? Once I warm up to you ,I'm sure we will have nothing but good times!

animal.description:
Available for adoption starting December 23rd at 7:00pm on our website under the Adoptions Uncrated program, followyourheartanimalrescue.org/shop.

Wilbur is a handsome, smart, energetic boy. He knows many commands including sit, down, stay, place, heel, paw, and roll over. He is crate trained as well. 

However, like a lot of teenagers, he sometimes forgets his manners and jumps up to say hello instead. He gets crazy zoomies and loves his toys. Sometimes in his excitement he misses the toy and can catch hands instead. He doesn't mean harm just lots of excitement and energy. 

He wasn't properly socialized as a young puppy so he can be rude and sometimes reactive with other dogs so he would love the chance to get to be your one and only. 

You should also know he really loves armpit scratches, so please be willing to accommodate. Wilbur LOVES to work and play, he is not a chill on the couch kinda dude, but if lots of fetch and training games and a high energy ready to go friend is what your looking for he is your man. Because of his abundance of excitement we recommend he not go to a home with young children.

animal.description: If you could describe May in four words, it would be cute, smart, proper, and loyal! This adorable lady gets along great with a 75lb pit bull in her foster home, and her beard is just precious. This crate-trained and house-trained gal has never had an accident in the house, and she really enjoys her daily walks. She is generally great on the leash, but can respond to some dogs but not others. She would definitely benefit from additional leash etiquette lessons. She also goes right in at the 'kennel' command for a treat and is calm and quiet while inside, so you can rest easy while you are away on your errands. She will 'sit, for treats, but won't always hold the sitting pose. May would ideally love a low-traffic home with a human who is experienced with special dogs. We don't know everything about May's history, but she has a tendency to be mouthy, and would love a human who can continue training her on redirection. May can be a little wary and will come by her humans and seemingly ask for pets, but it's important to only engage in pets with her consent, especially when meeting new people. An ideal home for May would be an adult only, low-traffic house with not many visitors, and with someone who is experienced at handling mouthy pups. She could also do well with another doggie friend that matches her energy. Come meet May, her beard will bring a smile to your face!

animal.description:
Location: Gloucester, VAHi, the name is Zeus! And I am in the market for a new home for the holidays and for all the days of my life. Could that be you? Let me tell you about myself. Not only am I happy and affectionate, I used to live on a farm. My former family had to give me up through no fault of my own, but they speak highly of me. I lived with another dog and we got along fine. She was a submissive female. I like to swim in the creek, ride in the car and am happy to go in a crate. I also got along with the peacock. How many dogs do you know that have a peacock for a friend? But I didn't get along with the pigs, or the cats. The stress of the pound makes me grumpy with other bully dogs and we get rowdy through the fence or gate, so if you have or plan to have me around other dogs, you will need to do a meet and greet with them. Of course, I would love to be an only furry child. I need to catch up on my couch cuddles. In my former home, I loved visiting with children and I love to walk on the leash. A fenced in yard would be great too as I have lots of playful energy. I take treats gently and appear to be at least partially housebroken, as I do my biz the minute we go outside.

Sadly, I am heartworm postive and will need to be treated for them. The local humane society will pay for and do the treatments. After that, you can do what is called a foster to adopt, where I come to live with you while I finish up my treatment. At the end of treatment, you can officially adopt me. Oh how I long for the day to be adopted and have my own home again!

If you want to know more about my personality, please contact Joyce at 757-376-8360 or email at jemerson60@hotmail.com

I am at the Gloucester Animal Control pound at this time and have been here since I arrived. However, all adoptions are administered by the Gloucester Mathews Humane Society . To apply for my adoption, please contact them at animalplacement@gmhumanesociety.org. If you have a vet, you might want to let them know that they will be contacted so you can give permission for them to give information.

Please come meet me, I will give you lots of loving and will be your new best friend.
animal.name: Zeus in Gloucester VA

animal.description:
1/21/21 Update on Danny Boy's adoption status: Danny  is still available and we are still looking for a home with the perfect yard for him.  It is out there, somewhere. He did have a home lined up, but the people decided that they did not want to take the responsibility of keeping him safe. We understand, it's a serious responsibility indeed.

He has had two surgeries in less than 6 months to remove stones/rocks from his belly and intestines. We are looking for a back yard that has NO rocks or stones. None, period. You must have  pavers/concrete/artificial turf only.  Natural grass ALWAYS has rocks and stones working their way to the surface.  No, it is not nutritional. He's been tested.  No, we will not rely on training. Most trainers agree that a clean environment is the safest thing for him.  No, a few rocks won't work. Rocks are rocks. No, it's not boredom.  
 
Danny's foster mom said "We  have natural grass and he always wears a muzzle or Outfox head mesh when he goes outside. My fervent wish is to find a back yard where he will be able to go out without those devices, and people who are willing to use them whenever he is outside elsewhere."
 
If you can meet these requirements and are looking for a sweet, dog and cat-friendly, 4-year-old purebred English Cream Golden and would like to talk, you can email info@arizonagoldenrescue.org.

Danny Boy is a handsome, neutered 4-year-old English Creme Golden.  He was returned to the breeder when the owner passed away a few month ago. We did not receive much information from the breeder at intake, so we only know what we have learned the past month in foster care..
      
Danny loves his food and was up to 112 pounds at one point, but is a svelte 87 now. It's a good weight for him - he is a big boy. He had surgery 4 months ago for eating rocks and he continues to seek out and swallow them when he can. Danny is loving, people and dog-friendly and is not destructive when left alone, but will counter-surf if given the opportunity. In addition to rocks, he enjoys empty dog food cans, plastic containers and carrots for treats. He loves to play but can also sit and chill out. He loves the couch and cuddling on the bed, but could learn to stay off if needed. He loves to ride in the car and going on walks. Danny Boy is very strong, but walks very well on a leash when using a Gentle Leader or similar head halter. 

Danny was very matted when he came in but has since had a grooming and trim. When his coat comes in it will be medium length and not difficult to maintain.

There are many options with rock-eating dogs to try to train and modify their bad habits, but we feel the safest environment for him is a rock/gravel-free yard. It is also recommended by veterinarians and trainers to use a basket muzzle on him when he is loose in an area that has rocks - such as parks, woods, etc. However, he does not need that on a leashed walk.

If you are interested in meeting Danny Boy, you must fill out an application and have a home visit to begin the approval process..   WE DO NOT ADOPT OUTSIDE OF THE STATE OF ARIZONA.   If you are interested in Danny, please visit our webpage at arizonagoldenrescue.rescuegroups.org/info/adoption  and complete an Online Adoption Application to begin the process, or send an e-mail to info@arizonagoldenrescue.org if you have questions and wish to be contacted.

Prior to adoption, all AGR dogs are given a full vet exam, including valley fever and heartworm tests, brought up to date on all vaccinations, given a microchip, neutered or spayed, and treated for any medical problems.
animal.name: Danny Boy

animal.description: If we could snap our fingers and instantly, magically deposit one shelter dog into a loving home right now, it would be our little gremlin Thunder.  At 2, this very good boy had to recently come back to us after nearly a year and a half in a loving, happy home.  His fosters-turned-adopters worked so hard to build up his confidence and shape him into the very good boy he is today.   He ADORED their other dog, who became his best friend and guide to living with humans.  But, lately, Thunder was showing signs he was frightened of their toddler.  They were broken-hearted to bring him back, but this was absolutely the safe and right decision.    Now that we have a clearer idea of Thunder’s needs, we would love to see him in an adult home with a companion dog who can show him the ropes.  Thunder is sweet, curious, house-trained, great with other dogs and bashful with new humans.  He is so eager to be your friend. Thunder is much-loved at PAWS Atlanta and we’re determined to help him to find a home in which he can thrive and be happy.  He is playful and resilient and is just a great young dog.

The volunteers at AGPR are working with me on my manners.  I get so excited to be with people that I like to jump up and give lots and lots of hugs...they are trying to teach me "four on the floor" and to wait to be invited up for hugs.  It is tough...I so want to hug everyone I meet.  But, I'm also food motivated, so I need to make decisions between hugs or treats.  Now do you see my dilemma?

My future home has to be CAT FREE and SMALL ANIMAL FREE.  I just don't like or trust those small critters...they are tricky!  I'm not a city boy...I'm still growing, have lots of energy and need a family willing to work on my manners.  In return, they will have my unconditional love (unless someone else offers me a tasty treat).

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org.  There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone!

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/  Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization.  We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Taco and I was born April 27th and growing every day. I will be a medium sized dog when I'm fully grown and will likely top out somewhere around 35-40lbs. My foster mom and I have been guessing my breed and think some type of frenchie, corgi, terrier mix, but she says it doesn't matter because I'm just a big snuggle bug of love. Whoever adopts me will have a loyal sidekick for life. When you call me to you, I will run to you like a speeding bullet and JUMP in your lap for the biggest hug ever. I am great with kids, other dogs and cats who like dogs. I have a few quirks for my young age so I am very clear on the type of home that I'm looking for. Here are my pre-requisites, and these are non-negotiable for me! 

-I need an experienced dog owner. I have been working on my fear of men, crates, and resource guarding in my foster home and need someone who will continue that work diligently with me!
-I need another dog in the home with me who is either a patient medium/large breed dog, or a small breed pup who can hold their own with a larger fur sibling, who will help continue to teach me good manners around dogs. I also LOVE to play and spend time with my foster fur siblings, so I'd really like to have another dog in the home to keep me stimulated and happy! 
-And last, but not least, I need my experienced owner to take me to beginners obedience classes. This will help me with continued socialization around other dogs and men, and also teach me the right boundaries around how to behave in my new home.

I KNOW I will flourish in a house like this and I hope that the perfect home is out there looking for a perfect dog like me. I will bring you all the joy in the world and will be your fiercely loyal companion for years to come! 

Applications are at https://bit.ly/codys_adoption_application. Cody's does not adopt puppies under the age of six months into apartment homes.

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Goose!! I am a super sweet three-year-old pittie who loves playing with my foster brother and sisters as much as possible. I also love sitting on the couch watching TV when I am not playing inside.

I am an owner surrender due to my timidness and fear. My previous owner originally rescued me in Charlotte, NC over two years ago. Because of my past, I am nervous around strangers and bark/back up but am NOT aggressive at all!

Once I see I can trust you, I will be your best friend! I may still bark if you surprise me but quickly calm down. I will need an experienced dog owner who will have the patience to let me get to know and trust them. If you have a friendly dog I can be buddies with it would help me even more with my confidence as my foster brothers and sisters have done for me in my current foster home. The best thing for me would be if my bestie Ramen could be adopted with me too! She makes me so so happy and makes me feel secure ans safe.

I am totally house trained as well as crate trained and exceptionally good on a leash for long walks or jogs. I love car rides but I have not been with small kids and have not been tested with cats. I eat alone or in my crate and would have to take it slow if I eat with a future brother or sister.

I am looking for my furever home where I can give you all the love I have in my heart!

If you are interested in adopting, please visit our website and complete an adoption application at www.elpasocountycanine.org/adopt

animal.description:
Maya is a beautiful Shepherd/Belgian Malinois mix who was found in the streets of Salinas. Saved off the streets where she was observed to have no understanding of the consequences of running in traffic, Maya completed her hold at the shelter after the good Samaritans were unsuccessful in finding her owners. 

Maya appears to have lived her previous life in a homeless situation and took a few days to adjust to being inside in her first shared foster homes while we waited for her spay and recovery. Maya was fortunate to have two family friends care for her. In one household, she lived with two resident shepherds and in the other with an American Pit Bull and another pit mix smoothly transitioning between households to accommodate schedules. Maya is currently sharing her foster home with a dog-savvy cat and three shepherds. Maya is a dominant female willing to test boundaries to establish her preferred spot in the dog pack. Since she is very people affiliative, she would be delighted to live as an only or with an easygoing, confident male dog.

Comfortable in the car for adventures, Maya is also potty and crate trained. She had reliable recall off-leash with her prior fosters; she hasn't been off-leash outside of her current foster home. Maya has excellent household manners, sleeps in her crate quietly at night. She likes to stick by her people with excellent eye contact for guidance. Bonded with the male resident shepherd her age, they spend hours playing with similar play styles. 

Maya's super playful and in each of her foster homes gravitates to a favorite playmate. She is agile, swift, and a joy to watch. Although Maya lacks the off top energy and busyness of a Belgian Malinois, she still needs a daily exercise routine appropriate for her age and energy level. She has been getting worn out by her buddy's play needs, slowing down for long nap near her people. Maya will make an excellent running, hiking partner. She is working on heeling, loves to be leashed up for walks. Although she will chase balls and run with them, she hasn't figured out the bringing back part. Maya also loves soft toys, digging in to find the squeakers and then using remnants of the toys for tug of war with her best friend. 

When Maya discovers a favorite new toy, she hides them around the house and yard, carefully picking her hiding spot to retrieve later. Sometimes they are out in the open, in a corner, or tucked under furniture. She is learning to navigate things that spook her, such as the sound of the garage door opening and closing, when something falls on the ground like the mop handle. It appears as she may have been mistreated at some point as she will pancake if a stick is thrown for fetch. 

So far, she is indifferent to the resident cat who has established order with her. Her original finder also told us she was good with her kids. Maya has not spent time with the kids in her foster homes. 

With a little time, patience, and love, Maya grants her trust. She will nudge hands to continue getting petted, put her head on laps, and sit smooshed next to her people for naps and belly rubs. With that trust, her forever family will be rewarded with a beautiful young, active, and affectionate partner. 

Maya is terrified of veterinary care constraints and needs to be desensitized to conquer her fears. She may need to be medicated to initially reduce her anxiety for vet visits. 

Maya is currently fostered in Sacramento and is available to meet approved adopters committed to enhancing their bond with Maya with patience, structure, and training.

animal.description:
IMPORTANT!!!   All adoptions are by appointment only going forward and are spaced 30 minutes apart. PLEASE call the shelter directly during business hours for more information (see number below).  You need to make sure that the animal in which you have an interest is still available and to set up an appointment to meet the specific animal.  Once you arrive at the shelter for your scheduled appointment, please follow the directions that you were given over the telephone. If you are running late for your appointment or will be unable to make your scheduled appointment time, notify staff immediately. This will enable them to schedule that time for another prospective adoptive family. If necessary, they will be able to reschedule your appointment to a more convenient time.  

MURPHY is a white and brown American bulldog. He ended up at the shelter with a notation on his cage card that he reportedly had been aggressive with other dogs and children. Apparently, he had been nipping at the feet of children and other dogs. In  some dogs this can be considered breed specific behavior, especially if they are herding dogs. While staff consider him a very sweet dog at the shelter, they believe it is important for potential adopters to understand the reason they do not want him to go to a home with other dogs and children. You can check with them by telephone to ask questions about this dog or any other dog that you may be interested in adopting. They may or may not know the circumstances beyond the information that was provided and posted to the cage card. If you do have dogs already or young children in your home, please do not call them and ask about adopting this dog. They do their very best to make sure that dogs are placed in suitable homes with responsible people to protect the community and the animals, as well. They need your help to make that happen. If you do not have other dogs or young children in your home, staff would welcome your call to schedule an adoption appointment to meet him in person. MURPHY has not yet been neutered. So, please read the important information below. 

Adoption fees are $80 for dogs.  Cat adoption fees are $50. Cash or check only. Please be sure to take the exact amount with you.

NOTE: All shelter fees are under review and may be changed or modified at any time without advance notice.

The shelter routinely vaccinates all healthy appearing animals upon their arrival at the shelter and deworms them.  Any animals not already spayed/neutered must have the procedure done through the veterinary clinic that contracts with the county before that animal can be released from the clinic to the new family. By state law, animals old enough to be given a rabies vaccine, must have that vaccine done, as well.  The vaccine is given by the veterinary clinic staff at a separate cost to the adoptive family. 

Hold periods for every incoming animal vary for several reasons including, but not limited to, whether the animal came in from the Cumberland County area, or from the City of Crossville, which contracts with the county for its animal shelter services.  Check with the staff to verify the availability date of every animal for which you have an interest.

For more information on this pet, call the shelter at (931)484-8525. The shelter is open Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday from 10am to 2pm. Closed Wednesday and Sunday and county observed holidays.

My name is KANE and I'm approximately 5 years old male chinese sharpei. I have been at the Agoura Animal Care Center since November 23, 2020. 

This handsome guy is 5 years old. He enjoys being pet, loves a real room lounge, a stroll around the kennels on leash, and spending time with the ladies!

He was terrified when he arrived at the Care Center. He’s not had an easy go of it prior to arrival with us - evidence of a long since healed possible burn to his back which caused fur loss and abandonment by his prior person left Kane heartbroken & scared. 

While he wasn’t sure he wanted to be friends with us at first, we quickly found he’s a “ladies man” and gave him time ( and plenty of treats!) with the women on our special teams. He quickly learned he was safe, and though sometimes a bit insecure, he now seeks attention, enjoys pets, and is good on a leash. 

He’s missing fur on his back by his tush, we aren’t sure why but appears to have been some kind of a burn long since healed. 
•
Kane is looking for an adult only true forever home.?(he’s been abandoned twice) A calm dog companion would be ok but no small dogs please. 

To inquire about Kane please email agoura@animalcare.lacounty.gov (Please include your contact number).
