animal.description: Roscoe is such an incredible guy. Once he has decided that you are his human, he'll be your most devoted and loyal boy. He knows this is a scary world, and he'll trust you to keep him safe. He'll become your love bunny, sitting with his head on your lap while you watch TV and hoping for pets and grooming for his soft, shiny coat. Now in foster, this boy spins in circles and wags his tail with excitement when it's time to go for walks, or play those games of fetch that he loves. He's already a skillful dude who understands 'sit,' 'down' and 'place.' And he understands that 'off' means to take his Kong toys, Nyla bones and ropes off the couch and bed. Roscoe walks well on his leash and usually is good when seeing other dogs. However, he has a 'stranger danger' problem. He is fearful of other people he sees and needs continued training to help him understand that strangers are okay. His training is beginning to help resolve this, and should continue. At home, he's becoming a couch potato who's happy to dream the afternoon away while his people work, just coming up to put his head on their laps for some loving. He's also a house-trained boy who will hop in his crate to snooze. And he's excellent when left home alone, happy to stay in his crate or roam freely. This sweet boy hopes for a big home with a huge yard and adults who can play fetch with him, take him on long walks - and continue his training to help him continue becoming confident and secure with all people he meets. See more of him on Instagram at @alenavictoriab.

animal.description: Jimmy was adopted by a family from another animal organization in 2018.  He had been diagnosed with a congenital skin disease called ichthyosis.  This disease caused his skin to flake.  He needs baths in medicated shampoo a couple times a week in order to keep it under control.  But here is the great stuff about Jimmy!  He is one of the most well behaved and sweet dogs you could ever meet.  He is an American Bulldog born on 5/13/18.  He is wonderful with other dogs and likes to play, but is mostly very chilled out.  He enjoys a  good game of tug, but then also enjoys chilling on the couch.  He is crate trained, leash trained, and housetrained.  He is fantastic with kids.  However, the family who adopted him has a 3 year old who is irrationally fearful of Jimmy.  They have worked with a couple trainers who have both said Jimmy is perfect!  The child is terribly afraid though to the point that the 2 just can't coexist.  Can you give this wonderful boy a chance?  His skin condition is holding him back from being taken back in by the organization who adopted him out.  He just needs a family who is willing to help him out with his disease and give him a great new forever home.

animal.description:
I’m  Pop-Pop, a male salt and pepper Miniature Schnauzer (probably with chihuahua) mix who is about six years old and weighs about ten pounds with natural ears and tail. SRT rescued me from a shelter when my owners didn't want me back.  When SRT picked me up, they recognized immediately that I had some neurological issues. They took me straight to a specialty neurologist and I've been diagnosed with some pain in my cervical spine and also I have something called hydrocephalus or commonly known as water on the brain. This condition is more common in toy breed dogs. My doctor thinks with medication I can lead a good quality of life. I have some medications I will need to be on for life. I'm house and crate trained and love to play with my toys. I tend to stockpile them up. I'm fine with other dogs, but I would be happy to be your one and only. I love going on car rides and my foster mom takes me all the time. I can't jump up on furniture, but a comfy dog bed is just fine for me. I sleep quietly in my crate at night. I'm a special needs boy and need an all adult home. Click the Adopt tab, complete your application, and put me, Pop-Pop, as a pup of interest. My  adoption fee is $300
.
Please visit our website at www.schnauzerrescuetexas.me to adopt or to see our other minis

From Scooby's foster mom...
I've fostered many dogs and Scooby may be  one of my favorites. If you are looking for the quintessential active, affectionate guy, look no farther, Scooby is 72 Lbs and 1.5 years old. He has a great personality like a young Lab, Shepski type. He's very attentive, eager to please, is always smiling, happy, playful, friendly, loyal, affectionate and just an awesome all around dog companion. Scooby has the most adorable facial expressions and soulful eyes. He is a young pup in a large sized body, he's enthusiastic, great with all people and loves to give and get affection from everyone. He played with a Beagle puppy the other day and likes my neighbors Yorkshire Terrie. He may not realize his size yet and could use a little more training but he's pretty darn great. Plus he's housetrained, good in the car and loves a good game of fetch. What's not to love! Scooby is all about the love. He wants to bring joy happiness to his humans. With an active lifestyle, Scooby is medium energy in the home. If you are lucky enough to adopt Scooby, count yourself blessed. Please do not email or message us about Scooby, instead fill out an application. Thank you, https://www.welcomehomesanctuary.org/

animal.description:
Due to COVID concerns, only Texas applicants will be considered.

Initial Bio 12/17/20: Teddy B is approximately 7 years old and about 10 pounds. He recently came to us from the Valley where he was found as a stray, then adopted, but ultimately returned to the shelter after some medical issues. Our sweet Teddy B has cardio megaly, which is an enlarged heart. He's being treated for some fluid due to total neglect. He has a cough, but we suspect that to dissipate. His bloodwork is absolutely perfect, so the vets feel this maybe congenital and he will have many years to give his owner. 

We also feel this baby was a breeder due to his love of the crate. He is the sweetest boy and likely had a home once upon a time. As I said, Teddy knows exactly what a crate is and that he is to eat in there, his choice. He will curl up next to us on the couch, but if we get up or leave the room we almost always come back to find him in his crate- his safe space- with his blanket. We initially tried to let him sleep in bed with us, but after finding him cowering in the corner by the door, we quickly realized that for now he's most comfortable in his crate and thats' okay.

 A potential adopter will need to have a crate and be comfortable with using it until he feels comfortable without it. I've never heard him bark and he startles when making sudden movements. He wants to be your shadow and stay close for snuggles. He doesn't steal food from the other dogs bowls even when its left out and knows not to beg for food while we are eating- even when my 1 year old drops it on the floor for the dogs lol. 

Right now he is wearing a belly band, which he is using likely out of fear or anxiety and because of his meds for his heart. Teddy can at times be a very nervous boy, which makes us sad to think of what environment he's previously experienced, but we know that he deserves the very best forever home which can help him through all the normalcies of a loving life. He would likely benefit from a home in which someone is around most of the day. Feel free to email us for questions at uyrfoster23@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Momma Rosie was surrendered to a high-kill shelter weeks away from giving birth after her human-dad abandoned her. While he was gone she had a Hollywood rendezvous with the lady’s shitzu and it sparked her final project- THE BULLSHITS (pit bull terrier and shitzu mixes)! Yet, despite what we were told from the previous owner these babies have continued growing and growing, and they are a WHOPPING 8-10 pounds at only 7 weeks old.
We are guessing there was truly some Great Pyrenees in the mix. These adorable, long haired babies are beautiful and will be big teddy bears. Carmen Miranda is up to date, fully dewormed and microchipped. She is ready for her forever home! 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
Meet the adorable Bodie!

Bodie arrived to the Humane Society as a transfer from ACCT Philly back in July of 2020. This handsome young man is around 5 years old and is UTD on vaccines, microchipped and neutered. 

Since arriving from the very busy and overcrowded shelter, we have learned a lot about this red meatball. Bodie is a very calm boy in his kennel, where you can always find him snuggled up in a pile of blankets with his favorite toy. Bodie love his favorite toys so much that you can always find them in his mouth! You guessed it, the way to this guys heart is through a ball!

Staff and volunteers at our shelter have deemed Bodie a "Staff Favorite" and he has really shown everyone how loving he is. Bodie loves his friends so much that he would love nothing more than to sit on your lap with a toy in his mouth and receive all the attention! Because he loves attention so much, Bodie would do best as an only pet. You read that right, Bodie is not a socialite by any means and prefers his people all to himself so no other pets in the home for this guy!

Bodie, like all dogs, could continue to use work on his quirks. You see, Bodie gets so excited some times that he just can't control his mouth. He is a nippy lad, who will need a strong, breed experienced owner willing to work on his quirk to allow him to be the very best boy he can be. In transparency, it is our duty to inform all potential adopters of this quirk as some may perceive it as aggression. Bodie is not aggressive, but due to his quirks and need for continued training, he will require his forever family to have no children.

Bodie is currently NOT available for adoption, however is looking for a LOCAL FOSTER home that is willing to allow him to crash with them while we straighten out some medical concerns that we have noticed over the last month or so. animal.description:
Up for Special Needs adoption - China! She is a 10+ year Chinese Crested pup under 25lbs. 

She's not exciting, but once she gets used to you (and vice versa) she's quite nice. Even though she's blinded by cataracts (like looking through a foggy window) she knows where her bed is, knows where the water bowl is, knows that the other dogs in her foster home go out the back door and stands there waiting to go out when she needs to potty. She has to be carried to grass and accompanied the whole time, but she's prompt and waits patiently to be picked up when finished. She has a typical old lady appetite, just a little warm water on kibble, thanks.

She still needs a dental and needs checked for a spay prior to being adopted. She will need lifetime drops to her eyes to try to keep her cataracts from becoming painful and Apoquel or some other maintenance treatment for itching. Otherwise, she'll be happy to keep a dog bed and blankets warm all day and night.

If you have a place in your heart (and your home) for China, apply at rescuedohio.org. China's adoption fee is $195.

SEX:  Female

COLOR:  Black and Tan
COAT:  Long
UP TO DATE:  10/20/2020
SPAYED/NEUTERED:   Before Rescue
DHPP:  yes               DATE: 10/20/2020
RABIES: 10/20/2020             TAG NUMBER: 97840
ADOPTION FEE:  275.00+20.00(chip fee)
HOUSETRAINED:  Yes
CRATE TRAINED:  No need to crate her
LEASH TRAINED: yes
FENCED YARD NEEDED:  Yes
SPECIAL NEEDS:  no
HOME W/ SMALL CHILDREN or GRANDCHILDEN:  NO
HOME W/ OTHER DOGS:           MALE:  yes        FEMALE:  yes
HOME W/ CATS:  unknown
MICROCHIP BRAND and #:   911PetChip  991003911125282  
MONTHLY HEARTWORM DATE: 20th of each month 
FOSTER HOME:  Linda  linda.southergill@att.net
RESCUE #:  2020-10-31-01
BIO:
Malibu came from a shelter in Southern Alabama, left at the gate in a box. She was terrified but we were contacted and pulled her into our rescue. Nothing but the good life from here on out baby!!

Our wants for her:
•	Adopted out into the southern states ONLY because she needs warm weather to walk to get this weight off her
•	Fenced in yard
•	Another small dog for her to pal around with NO big dogs
•	No apartments or high rises
•	No men or kids she’s scared of them!

I'm very sweet! I know because my foster Mommy says so all the time. I'm looking for somebody who will love me for forever and work on a little problem I have. I'm a bit chunky! I need someone who will take me on walks and be patient with me. I get tired and need to stop for a second or two and then continue my walk. I really do enjoy getting out. I've already started losing weight. My foster Mommy is very good at watching my diet and she got me this bright red sweater that is so toasty when we
go walking. She explained to me that it is very important I continue to lose weight. We dachshunds have a problem called IVDD (invertebrate disc disease), if we get too heavy our backs go out and we than can become paralyzed in the back. It can cost over $14-16K for the surgery! So I need someone to love me lots and take me for walks and watch my diet. 
I love my belly rubbed and I love all my babies (stuffed animals) . At night I am all about being tucked in and I sleep all through the night in my 
comfy bed .Mommy calls me a snuggler! I also love bubble baths, I had one the other night and the hair dryer doesn't bother me either. I get along with other small dogs but I'm true dachshund and don't like big dogs at all. And in my mind I'm a big time squirrel hunter !! 

Well, if I sound like the perfect dog for you please fill out an application.
 
============== Information for All Dogs/Adopters ==============

If you have questions about this dog, please feel free to contact the foster home at the email address listed above.  They have the most up-to-date information concerning the dog and would be happy to answer any questions about the animal. 

We welcome out of state and Canadian adoptions, but we will not ship any dog via cargo.  You will have to make arrangements to pick up the dog or for them to go by ground transport.  If you choose transporting by either volunteers through our organization or by paid transporter, there will be an additional $45 fee added for the required Health Certificate. 

We will not adopt into CT, RI, NH, ME, or MA due to strict laws regarding importation of dogs into those states.  If you have an issue with this, you need to take this up with your legislatures.

To understand the adoption process through AADR, please review the Adoption Information on our home page.  Transportation options are outlined on that page in Step 3.

If you are interested in adopting this Dachshund please review Read Before You Adopt and then you can complete an Application.

THANK YOU FOR YOUR INTEREST IN A RESCUE.

Please don't let the distance stand in your way of finding your newest best friend. We have volunteers that will help your "new friend" get up and down the East Coast and Mid-West. We just can't get them from one Coast to the other but some day we hope to have enough volunteers to do that as well.  For now, please look for dogs on your coast.

animal.description:
Meet Leela, a large 5yr old Shepherd/Malinois mix! She loves people and is well trained. She knows sit, wait/stay, kennel, come, down, and even shake. The only thing Leela loves more than people is getting belly rubs, and lots of them! She is fully house trained with no accidents and kennel trained where she likes to calmly wait for her people to come home from work/school. She is still getting used to walking on a leash and needs to learn manners when meeting other dogs (she can be reactive/aggressive). She is calm and polite indoors and never begs or counter surfs. She adores being out and about on walks & could walk for hours if you wanted; but she likes being inside playing and getting pets from people too. She is calm around noises and new situations and in true shepherd fashion needs plenty of mental and physical activity to be healthy and happy. 

Her ideal home would have a fenced yard (wood or PVC), adults with kids over 8yrs old (if any) who love giving lots of pets and belly rubs & someone with Shepherd experience to handle the leash reactions.

Adoption Fee: $350 (cash/card only) 

Please contact our Dog Coordinator to learn more about Leela & to be put in touch with her foster Mom:

Jaime 651-324-1105 or Jaime3369@gmail.com

Due to the recommendations about the coronavirus, we are not able to have group adoption events at PetSmart.  We are, however, allowed to do individual adoptions so if you are interested in this pup/dog, please contact the foster listed above to set up a meeting.  We look forward to continuing to save dogs with you and will resume group adoptions as soon as we can.  Thank you for your patience and understanding.

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home.  An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home.  Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home & truly become comfortable.  There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption; discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, & 3 months.  We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.   

Last Hope, Inc. is an all volunteer, foster based, no kill rescue! You can see almost all of our dogs on Saturdays from 11am - 3pm at Lakeville PetSmart (located by Hy-Vee just off 160th & Pilot Knob) & Burnsville Petsmart (located just off Hwy 35E & County Rd 42 by Chianti Grill).

Policies: You do not have to have a fence to adopt a dog from us, but some dogs will require a fence or acres to play, or an active family who will make sure the dog gets the exercise it needs to be happy.  Some dogs do not have the temperament that will do well with young children.   

The Adoption Fee is not enough to cover the vet bills. Sales tax of almost 7.25% is also included in the adoption fee that you see. Please consider donating to Last Hope to help us save these animals!

CAN YOU FOSTER? By taking a dog or puppies temporarily into your home and then coming to our adoption days to help find them homes, we can save more! If you’re interested, please email our dog coordinator: jaime3369@gmail.com and give us your contact information and what you would like to foster and someone will get back to you! You can also apply to be a foster home on our webpage! In the upper left hand corner there’s a drop down tab with the link for canine foster home. Just fill it out online & submit! We will get back to you as quick as we can.

animal.description:
Meet Boston! This adorable, 2 year old boy will steal your heart the second you meet him! Boston was found as a lost boy on 12/11, and now he is looking for a loving family to call his own! Boston is a super sweet boy with a heart of gold and a love for treats. He is calm, easy going, and takes treats gently from hands. Boston will be a great family dog for any family looking for not only an affectionate cuddle bug, but also an adventurous boy that will love to go hiking and traveling with the family! Get to know and love this loving, 50 pound boy in run 801. His ID number is 626431. Boston is up-to-date on vaccines, now neutered, and will be microchipped, and heartworm tested upon adoption. He can't wait to start loving his new family!

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

animal.description: Dexter is about 9 years old, and his history is a mystery! He came to his foster mom when he was found tied up outside a Petsmart in the middle of winter with a broken leg. Dexter is very affectionate and loves to go for walks. He is docile, but he also has a little grouchy side too. He loves burying himself in his blankets and making a nest. Dexter has a screw in one of his front legs from when it was broken. He has a unique appearance and can be a little silly looking, with patchy fur. His foster mom took him to several vets to determine the cause. It was decided that since he is a blue tricolor chi, sometimes alopecia is genetically common in these dogs, so his fur is just a bit threadbare. Dexter has been around LOTS of other small dogs and does great with them. He is also good with cats. He is house trained and potty pad trained. He would do well with adults or older, gentle children/teens in a calmer home. Please feel free to reach out with any questions!

animal.description: You see this dog house in my photos? This is all I have to call my own, I don't even have a name. I was seen being abandoned in the middle of nowhere but the person that left drove away so fast those that saw it happen couldn't catch them. Instead, they contacted the local pound and ask that I be taken so no more hard cold come to me. My body shows the hardship of an old unloved dog, i'm not neutered and I have masses on my chest and legs that have not been examined by a doctor, and I hurt everywhere. I won't flinch at the dogs that growl at me as I walk past thier kennel. I won't take for granted the kindness of a human. The folks at this shelter and those at Always & Furever Midwest Animal Sanctuary are taking me to a vet right now to receive medical attention. I'm not young, I'm not healthy, but I'm here, and I matter.

animal.description: Baby has turned a corner and hopefully will be  ready soon for a home to call his own.  He was used to breed, arrived frightened and completely unsocialized and after 2 weeks of leaving him alone, he began to learn to trust and has become a loving little guy although still fearful,  We adopted him to a single human home and he regressed.  Baby runs and plays and does happy dances and wags his tail but still tends to keep to himself when approached and is currently happiest with a pack of dogs and being left to his own devices.  He seems to thrive on activity and commotion of the dogs and his runs with his pack. He will still take going slowly and no false moves until he settles in with someone when it comes to the one on one with humans. He will not work with children because of that. He should have an experienced and tolerant owner who will always respect him and care deeply for what he has been through during his formative years.  He will be an expensive dog to maintain, needing to be groomed frequently; his breed is considered high maintenance and unless regularly groomed will end up a mess like he was when we got him (his hair is VERY long)..  He also needed a dental at the young age of approx 3 so be prepared to be able to afford frequent dental needs going forward.  He is approximately 3 years old and we are asking an adoption donation of 345.00 and an application.  And a home that matches what is written above.  Dogs important and an active lifestyle with a fenced yard and space to run and play.

animal.description:
Natasha is a pretty girl with two distinct sides to her. On the one hand, she can be demure, sensitive and unsure in new situations, and takes some time to warm up. But once she starts feeling more comfortable, she reveals the firecracker within! Natasha may be on the petite side, but she is strong and determined on walks. This girl certainly seems food-motivated, and treats seem to be one way to fast-track into her heart! During quiet moments where she can relax, Natasha shows her sweet and affectionate side by trying to clamber in your lap for attention. She is somewhat anxious around other dogs so far and would likely need slow, gradual intros. She would likely do well in a calmer home where she can adjust at her own pace and blossom! Natasha is estimated to be around 3 years old and weighs 43 lbs.
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

Wendy Lou is a sweet & playful pocket pittie mix who is 2 years old and weighs 38 lbs.  She is a friendly, funny, "life of the party" kinda girl who will win your heart with the twinkle in her big brown eyes!  She is a medium energy girl with good leash manners and she's currently learning basic commands in her foster home.  She likes other dogs, likes to be busy, and likes to be a bit bossy with her canine friends.  She is housebroken, crate trained, spayed, fully vaccinated & microchipped.  Wendy is HW+ and is currently available for a foster to adopt situation until her HW treatment is complete and she is medically cleared for adoption. If you are not familiar with Heartworm disease, dogs get it from mosquitos and it is not contagious. It is highly treatable, but requires extended rest during treatment.

For more information about Wendy Lou, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet girl, please submit an application for her at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description: Hi there! My name is Diesel. I'm tall, dark, and you guessed ithandsome! Everyone here loves spending time with me and has learned a lot about my personality. I didn't have the best start to life; new strangers (especially men) can make me uncomfortable. I like to keep my friend circle small and cozy. Because new people can make me nervous, I am looking for a new family who really gets dog behavior. If I could describe my ideal home, it would have: a cozy, comfy bed, a pantry full of doggy snacks, great toys for chasing, a loving family, and a quiet, relaxing atmosphere. A fenced yard would be nice too, so I can run all over and act like a goof. Did you notice kids aren't part of my dream home? Yeahthey aren't very quiet, and I prefer the sophisticated company of adults, thank you very much! But I would maybe like a dog sister! No brothers pleasemale dogs always get in my space and I don't like that. Also, no small animals or cats for me! I love to keep busy chewing on a good snack or Kong, but I like to be alone when I enjoy a delicious snack; I mean, do you like it when people take your snacks away? I don't think so! Overall, I am a simply fella; I like to know my routine, what I'm doing everyday, but I need someone to spend my days with! I've been at the shelter for a long time, and I dream of my new family arriving to take me home. I know they are somewhere out there, I just have to be patient! I have a lot of hopes and wishes for my new family, so it might take a few meet and greets for me to find the perfect fit! Please give me a chance if you think we could be a match. If this dog has been successful in our play groups it is not a guarantee that a dog will be social with other dogs in their home or in public settings. Play groups do not guarantee that territorial or resource guarding issues will not surface in the home. While play groups do help us get to know the dog's better, once they are adopted their new environments and new relationships will influence their behavior in ways we cannot predict. The Adoption Fee Includes: - initial canine distemper combination vaccination - first worming or stool check - rabies vaccination (for animals over 3 months of age) - AVID microchipping - flea treatment/preventative - spaying or neutering - Leash and collar Adoption fee: $135.00 Per state law, ALL ADOPTERS must purchase a non-refundable 2021 dog license at time of adoption for any canine three months and older.

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullABOUT DUKE

Duke is a fun-loving boy who is still an energetic puppy! He has a high energy level and would love a family that would help him channel that energy into hikes, car rides and playing fetch! He is friendly with other dogs but, since he is still a youngster, he sometimes forgets how strong he is. He would do best with a family that is familiar with pitbulls and would help him become more socialized. He loves food and will do anything for a treat! If his people are otherwise occupied, Duke will entertain himself by throwing his toys, and especially tennis balls, for himself - who needs humans?! He loves to play fetch and explore, but NOTHING beats a good belly rub! Have to run errands? Duke is a great co-pilot! He lies down in the back seat and enjoys the ride! Duke sleeps in his crate at night and is generally a quiet boy. He loves people and may get a little too excited and jump on new people, but he can't help it - he loves everyone!

Duke would enjoy a family who is pitbull-savvy. He would love to have another dog to play with, but one who will help him learn "how to dog" more, especially socially. He'd do well with active older kids, but is likely to be too jumpy/strong for younger kids. He'd love to be part of your adventures- hikes, car trips - but can also be part of a family where he is alone some of the day since he does very well in his crate.

Duke just wants to be loved - don't you want to love him?

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and fed premium grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Oakley is a super special dog that needs a super special home! He’s a pit/mastiff mix at around 65 pounds and 4 years old. 
We don't know much about his history, other than he was a stray picked up and brought to a Caddo parish animal shelter.  He was completely shut down and emaciated at the shelter and was scheduled to be euthanized when he was pulled by Take Paws. He’s a beautiful, calm, gentle boy who deserves to finally know happiness.
For the past month Oakley has been living with a professional dog trainer where he has been given the opportunity to decompress, build confidence, and learn to trust. Oakley was initially extremely despondent and depressed, but has started coming out of his shell over the last few weeks more and more. He needs humans who will be patient with him and who will continue to help him progress in a calm, quiet house with little to no commotion. 
He’ll do best around low energy, balanced dogs who can show him that life isn’t always so scary. 
Oakley shows the most emotion when he goes on walks, where he walks perfectly by your side and does not pull in the slightest. He is not leash reactive, although he is scared of children. 
Oakley deserves a loving forever home!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
**Please read Mama Audrey's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. Thank you!** 

Meet Audrey! Audrey is a one year old mix of Mountian Cur, Australian Shepard & Mini Pinscher who weighs around 50lbs. She’s been an amazing mom to her 7 extra large pups but now it’s her turn to find a family of her own! Audrey is a little on the shy side and will need someone who is patient to let her blossom into her true self. She has low to average energy and is very content with walks (and is good on a leash) & hanging out with some chin rubs. She enjoys her Kong, lickibowl & snuffle mat.  She is housebroken as well.  We recommend her with calmer kids who are 10+. 

She’s quite the escape artist, so a securely fenced in yard is a must for this girl! It’s her turn to find a family who is willing to put in the patience, time and effort to help her become the best girl she can be!  Her white tipped tail hardly ever stops wagging to you are off to an amazing start with her enthusiasm and energy!
 
All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption.  All dogs require professional training to become the best family member they can be.

To adopt or learn more about Audrey, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $495]  **  PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

animal.description:
My name is Cookie, and I am as sweet as I sound. I have gorgeous brown eyes, and I love people, kids, walks, car rides, and playing in the water. I do not love other dogs or cats, so it would be best to walk me somewhere where I won't see other dogs. If you meet me at the shelter, I may be loud and bark a lot because I don't like those other dogs. But I promise I am so sweet when I'm not around them. 

I am a lovely medium energy level. I would love a backyard where I can run and play with you. I like to play and go for walks but I'm also really good at just snuggling up on a lap. I would do very well with someone who enjoys the outdoors as much as I do. You should see my cute hop when I run. I like to play with toys when I am hanging out inside the house. 

I am crate trained and house trained. I am very calm and loving around people I like to stand on my back legs and give hugs. Yes, hugs! I will wrap my arms around you and lay my head on your shoulder. I am goofy and affectionate, and I am looking for a fur-ever home. 

Ask about my discounted adoption fee and make an appointment to meet me today!
 (4 years old, 48 pounds, spayed, only pet, crate trained, house trained, kid friendly)

My name is Alexie and I am a 3 year old beautiful all natural girl who recently arrived in rescue from a shelter. I was taken there by my family and left there. I don't understand why.

I am a sweet girl. I am a bit timid when I first encounter new situtations but I warm up fairly quickly. I have lots of energy and love to run and play. I love attention from my humans. I ride very nicely in the car. More information will be posted on me as known. No cats. I would do best with a calm male but would need to be introduced to all dogs in the home.

If you are interested in me please review adoption criteria and area at www.doberescue-ne.org and if you qualify please place an application.All of our dogs are current with all shots, are on heart worm preventative monthly and are neutered/spayed. All dogs are tail docked. All of the above Dobes are pure breed Dobermans unless otherwise noted.We hope you can find a place in your heart and your home for one of our rescue Dobes.Please Note:In most cases we require a fenced yard.We do not place our rescue dogs in homes with very young children (under the age of 8 years). We set these limitations, not because of aggression issues with our dogs, but because Dobermans are generally large, active dogs and can easily knock down, run over or easily trip a small child, causing a serious fall. Also, we reserve the right to refuse adoption for any reason.Our adoption area encompasses Nebraska, Iowa and South Dakota.Copyright 2007 - Omaha Doberman RescueFor more information or to fill out an adoption request please visithttp://www.doberescue-ne.org/

animal.description:
Butters was rescued and pulled for our local shelter in Olive Branch, Ms.  She weighs about 61 pounds and is now spayed and current on all her vaccines and preventatives.  She had a large tumor removed from her chest and has recovered from that surgery along with her spay.  Our vet thinks she's about 5-6 years old.  She been quite content since that uncomfortable tumor has been removed.  She also has another surgery to go through to remove a small tumor on her front leg.  Our vet wants her to go through her heartworm treatment before the second surgery.  She can be fostered through her heartworm treatment and second surgery.  All that is covered through donations.  
She is quite selective of other dogs.  She could do ok with another male but doesn't get along with other female dogs.  She has not been around any small children but would be ok with older teenagers.  She loves her meal time and can be quite demanding at feeding times....she will let you know when breakfast and dinner need to be served.  Not sure about cats...she doesn't seem to bother the ones in her foster home but they are separated with a baby gate. Think a retired person who is home a lot and needing a companion would be a great match for Butters.  
Her adoption fee is $150 and her upcoming surgery and heartworm treatment is covered by Save1Pet.

If you are interested in adopting, we encourage you to fill out our adoption questionnaire at http://members.petfinder.com/~MS72/adoption_app.html

Save 1 Pet is a 501 (c) 3 approved charity committed to helping homeless animals.  We don't have a facility (shelter) but work out of our homes to foster the animals until they find a forever home.

Please be advised that for all adoptions, we will conduct reference checks, including veterinary references.  Our adoption fee for dogs includes spay/neuter, heart worm check, current vaccines, microchip, worming and heart worm/flea/tick prevention.
For dog adoptions, we do conduct fence verification.
When adopting an animal, you will be asked to complete our Adoption Contract

animal.description:
PLAYFUL AND ENERGETIC:  10 months old / 41 lbs. 

Hi there, my name is Branch!  I was adopted from Mostly Mutts when I was just a puppy, but my owner had a job change that requires a great deal of travel, leaving little time for me.  So, Mostly Mutts is helping me find a new home and family to love!  I’m currently participating in the prison/foster training program, where I will be learning lots of great commands and doggie manners.

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  No dogs please.  I am a very rough player and get overly excited and assertive in play – I just don’t know how to turn it off, so a home without other dogs is best for me.  I did accidentally bite a volunteer’s leg once when passing by another dog’s crate when we were both overly excited – I redirected to the volunteer – so sorry about that / Cats Unknown, but I don’t think so / I haven’t met kids yet at MM’s or in my previous home, but since I am a busy player, much older kids such as teens will likely be best – let’s meet and talk with my trainer. 

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am a very playful guy with big puppy energy and I’m affectionate, too.  I love being with people so much that I have separation anxiety and have started medication for it.  A dog savvy owner who is home a lot and wants to be active/exercising with their dog could be a good fit for me / My energy level is 7-9, so I am looking for an active family dedicated to my training and providing regular outlets for my energy.  I can see myself going for hikes, walks, maybe even some runs or camping.  The sky’s the limit.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY: I am a student in the Mostly Mutts University prison/foster training program, where I am learning lots of great doggie commands with my trainer and having fun at the same time.  Leash manners are top of my training list as I currently pull on my leash / I do not like being in a crate at all – we are going to try a special crate for me soon, so just ask about that / Though reportedly potty trained, I’ve had accidents since being at Mostly Mutts.  Perhaps I am just getting used to the schedule, so please be consistent with taking me out.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I love to play with toys and be active with my people, so let’s have some fun / I don’t like being alone or in a crate at all, and I wouldn’t be happy if I did not get regular exercise, training and the love I deserve!  

• MEDICAL:  I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and neutered. I’m on a medication for severe separation anxiety – my trainer will be glad to talk to you about this. 

I am looking for a dog savvy family that will be active with me and include me in on lots of fun as well as continue my training.  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

She is about 1 1/2 years old, spayed, microchipped, current on all her vaccines.  Unfortunately, she has tested positive for heartworms and is about finished with her heartworm treatment.  
She enjoys a good run in the yard.  Sadly, she hasn't really recognized any toys yet.  She has not been destructive and that's always good.  She loves to get belly rubs.  She doing much better on her kennel training.  We feel like she probably spent her early life in small pen area.  She still circles a lot but is learning there is plenty of room to explore here in her foster home.
She does not do well with other female dogs but really likes the boys here in her foster home.  She doesn't seem to be fazed by the cats in her foster home.
Her adoption fee is $150 and Save1Pet is covering her heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
TROOPER HAS SPECIAL MEDICAL NEEDS - DIABETIC

Playful, handsome foodie who enjoys long walks searching for soulmate!! Trooper is a very curious, playful, and energetic young boy who loves chew toys like Nylabones. While he also enjoys stuffed toys, they never last very long because he likes to de-stuff them and try to snack on the pieces! Trooper is a type 1 diabetic and receives insulin shots twice daily after eating. Due to the importance of his insulin shots, his ideal forever family would work from home or have staggered schedules allowing a caregiver to always be present when he needs them. Trooper's foster family says that while his condition is manageable, it is lifelong. Having a diabetic dog requires regular veterinary checkups and purchasing medication, so Trooper must be adopted by a family who is ready, willing, and able to commit to managing his diabetes for the rest of his life. To learn about diabetes in dogs please go to
Diabetes in Dogs: Symptoms, Treatment, Cost and Life Expectancy | PetMD T
ooper's biggest passion in life is food -- ANY food! Sometimes he will attempt to swipe snacks from the trash can or the kitchen table, which his foster mom reports is managed with consistent rules. Because of the diabetes, Trooper's diet needs to be monitored closely at all times. (He was hoping that we wouldn't share that last part with potential adopters.... ;) ) Trooper gets along well with other dogs. His foster mom reports that one of his favorite activities is playing with his canine foster sister! He also enjoys hanging out with his human foster siblings. While Trooper is not a cuddler, he is very sweet and affectionate and likes to lie next to his humans to get attention. He also loves going for walks with his people! He is currently learning to walk like a gentleman; he tends to pull on his leash to remain "part of the pack" if the other dogs he is walking with get ahead of him. Trooper knows basic obedience commands and is housebroken. He is crate trained, as well, although he will fuss a bit if he thinks it'll get him out of his crate! :) If you want to be Trooper's forever family, please submit an application today to adopt him!

animal.description:
Hello there, I'm Tony! I came to WSHS after being passed around from person to person, so now I'm looking for a stable forever home. Despite my rough start in life, I absolutely love people and want to be around them all the time. When people go away, I get anxious. I have separation anxiety, but we've been working on it here at the adoption center. I'm looking for a very special person or family to help me feel secure with a stable environment that has lots of routine and structure. Routine will help me anticipate what comes next so I don't get worked up about the unknown. Someone who can take me to work with them or a home where someone is always around would be a great match! Here at WSHS, I get to help out at the adoption desk by snoozing on a comfy bed by their work station. (It's very important work.) I need someone who wants a little shadow to follow them around all day.

Training classes will help me be the best version of me and help me gain confidence in my new home. My new home should have kids over 8 years old. Cats do not like how much I like them, so I can't live with cats. Playing with other dogs is one of my favorite things, but they sometimes don't like the way I play. If I'm to live with another dog, our play styles should be complimentary. Our initial meeting will include any dogs in your home so we can evaluate our compatibility. I can't live in apartments, townhomes or condos because of my barking. I'm a misunderstood little lover who is looking for his permanent forever home. Take a chance on me, you'll fall in love right away!

Please note - we always take our animals back if for some reason it doesn't work in your home so we only adopt to the following Illinois counties: Cook, DuPage, Kane, Kendall, Lake, McHenry, Will.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Griff!
Yes - he looks like a bear cub! Chows are unbelievably adorable and are often adopted because of how cute they are without people truly understanding the breed. Griff's foster mom has put together an impressive list of criteria for his adoption to help us narrow down ALL the applications we are sure to receive for this ridiculously cute guy.

Griff is approximately 2 years old, male, shaded black chow who weighs about 55lbs. He is looking for the following:

1 - experienced chow owner. He needs someone who has worked with Chows and knows how to be a good pack leader.
2 - a female dog sibling to play with or someone who can commit to taking him to a structured daycamp once or twice a week for socialization and play time.
3 - someone who owns their home. Not all rental properties restrict Chows, but many do. For that reason, homeowners will be given precedence.
4 - time and resources. Chows can be a tricky breed that require ongoing socialization with both humans and dogs. They need continued training, regular grooming and (especially for Griff, because of his history) a high quality diet.
5 - older children (at least 8 years old) who have experience with dogs and are respectful and savvy.

If you're interested in meeting Griff and seeing if he could be the perfect, handsome, fluffy guy to complete your family, apply to meet him today at rescuerovers.org

animal.description:
Meet Milo. Milo is a sweet 10 lb senior boy. He is an easy keeper and likes to hang out with his people and find a soft, warm place to nap on quiet afternoons. He has the most amazing, plushy brindle coat and an endearing, expressive little face. Milo sleeps quietly all night in his crate but loves to sleep on his person's bed too. He is housebroken when on a regular schedule and has existed peacefully with other dogs and cats. His superpowers include: napping, asking for petting (back and head scratches are just the best!), keeping a careful watch on the availability of any tasty tidbits, laying on the couch watching TV with his humans, and asking for attention with the cutest little voice. He is a good watchdog and will let you know when the delivery man is at the door. Milo is a special needs boy who came into rescue with a serious heart murmur. Due to his heart condition, Milo cannot go for long walks but gets excited to put on his harness and go for a walk around the block. He has responded well to treatment and is stable on his medication, which he needs for life. His medications cost approximately $60/mo and he requires regular check ups. This gentle boy is looking for his forever, retirement home.

If you are interested in adopting this pet, please fill out an application at https://www.hopeanimalshelter.net/petfinder. This pet is not located at our shelter. To meet this pet, please fill out an application, and our HOPE Fosters team will contact you in 24-48 hours. We are doing adoptions by appointment only at this time, so please fill out an application to start the process. Adoption fees range from $150-$240 (depending on age) and all adoption fees include spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations, and microchip with registration. Please email us at hopefostersaz@gmail.com to inquire about availability or for any other questions.

animal.description:
Head turner, good looking, handsome, striking, and hunky...all great ways to describe this cute boy, Theo! Not too mention he has a smile that will melt your heart. He has the cutest little white tip on his tail that catches in the sun as he wags it happily! Valentine's isn't very far away and maybe this boy will be the one to fill your heart with LOVE!

Need a co-pilot that doesn't "bark" directions?? Theo loves to ride along and just observe whats going on around him. He is excellent in the car so if you travel a lot; he'd be a great companion to keep you company on the road.

Theo is young & active and so a family that likes outdoor fun, jogging, hiking and those kinds of things would be idle for Theo. He is agile and could see him learning cool tricks! He is gets excited when 1st on a walk, but he knows and understands loose leash walking. With continued positive reinforcement, he will be an awesome exercise companion. He knows SIT and is learning other commands to be a polite boy. 

We are learning what kinds of other dogs Theo likes to play with right size, right energy level, and just the right fit.

Theo is a one-year old, 55lb male that loves attention. Hes good with other dogs,and should be supervised to ensure proper introduction and energy levels. He is way too interested in kitties, so no cats in the home. Theo is young and active so needs a family and/or other dogs that are a good match for him...watch his zoomie video :)! Young kids seem to make him nervous, so he will only be considered for a home with the appropriate age of children.

Theo is a very handsome boy and often turns heads. He is very photogenic and "plays to the camera" with his good looks and bright smile.

As part of Theo's $250 adoption fee, he is neutered, microchipped, up to date on vaccines, and current on his monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. If you have questions about this sweet boy, you can email Dogteam@pawsforlifenc.org. If you wish to adopt Theo, you can fill in an online application for him under the Adopt a Pet Tab on our website: www.pawsforlifenc.org.

If you would like to adopt a dog from Rescue Row please fill out an application at www.rescuerowinc.org

*Please check your junk email folder if you do not receive a response from a Rescue Row member within 48 hours.

*You must live within an hour of the DFW Metroplex because we do trial adoptions and require a homecheck

*Our adoption fees are as follows (paid by cash or a check made out to Rescue Row):

 Dogs 12 weeks-6 months old: $300 adoption fee

 Dogs 7 months and older: $275 adoption fee

Rescue Row is a 501(c)3 (non-profit) all volunteer dog rescue organization serving the DFW Metroplex. We are dedicated to rescuing dogs in shelters, dogs in abusive or neglectful situations, and dogs surrendered by their owners because of difficult circumstances. We place dogs in loving, responsible, committed permanent homes, following a comprehensive adoption process, which includes taking considerable care in finding good matches and educating prospective adopters about the responsibilities and costs of bringing a dog into their homes and lives. Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, microchipped, receive all appropriate veterinary care and treatment, and placed in nurturing foster homes while they await placement in their permanent homes. We assist dogs in distress without regard to age, breed or ease of placement. Dogs in the greatest need take priority. Finally, we strive to work with shelters and other rescue and humane organizations to develop a network of supporters and volunteers in order to create a better world for homeless dogs.

animal.description: There has been a few attempts by humans to describe me, but nothing seems as accurate as speaking for myself. My name is Zoya, and if I weren't so shy, I might actually say hello to more people. But people worry me, and I am learning to open up and trust them. I've never been mean to a human, in fact, I'd rather run from them than spend time with them... they always seem to want to grab me, touch me, or stare at me with their teeth shining at me... rather terrifying when I don't really know what all that means from a human, but in dog language it isn't very comforting. I like the people I have come to know, they feed me, pet me, talk calmly to me, and let me play with all these other dogs in the pack. I think I'd like my own family, but it would have to be a calmer household with a yard, and maybe I'd do better if I had another dog with me that could help me interpret what human behaviors really mean. I'm quiet, shy, generally polite, and with patience and time, I get to like my small world of people. I don't pee in the house, don't mind cats, and am not a very vocal dog. I'm nervous about the world when I go on walks, but I'm not rude or aggressive in any way. So, if you are a patient, quiet person, maybe with another dog in the home, perhaps we should meet. Don't expect too much of me at first, but eventually, as we get to know one another, I'm pretty sweet and loyal.

animal.description:
Jake is a 3 year old Staffordshire Terrier mix who, despite his young age, has been through the wringer. Jake was rescued from a high kill shelter in Texas and has been undergoing heartworm treatment ... and takin' it like a champ! Jake's a month shy of his final checkup and ready to find his furever fam. According to Jake's foster, "he is a GREAT dog! He absolutely loves and adores our kids and he's amazing with them. He'll be a hard one to let go!" This happy-go-lucky, playful young dog loves an active home (kids, please!), his basket of stuffy toys, other dogs, and fun games like tug and wrestle. Jake is a big, silly, lovebug that sometimes forgets his size; therefore, it might be best if all children in the home are over the age of 8. Jake is kennel trained and is proud to show you how he can "sit" and "stay". In his foster home he's working on learning additional commands including how to not bolt out the front door. Jake will need a home with a sturdy, large fence because this smart, strong boy can easily maneuver himself over a regular chain link. This southern boy is still adjusting to brutal winter weather so right now he is having the occassional accident but, by and large, Jake is house trained. This sweet, lovable boy is always ready for an adventure - backyard or road trip - as long as it's with you!

Before applying to adopt Jake, you need to be familiar with your local breed-specific legislation regarding Pit Bulls. Applicants must live within 50 miles of the Omaha/Council Bluffs area. 

The suggested adoption donation for Jake is $350. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

Hello! My name is Copper. I am an 11 month old 60lb lover boy! I am a Pit bull mix. I am hoping to find a furever home soon as I really just want to settle down. Sadly, my family could no longer keep me due to having another baby. 

I am good with other dogs and like to play and rough house. I was good with the kids in my previous home, however, my new family should keep in mind that I like to play nip sometimes. I am working on leash training as I am a pretty strong guy, but I learn quick. I am house trained. Crate training is a work in progress, I really do not like it. While I do like to play, really I am happy just hanging out on the couch.

Being rehomed was really hard on me. I really loved my family and I am having a hard time understanding why they are gone. Therefore, I can be standoffish with strangers, especially men. However, after about 30 mins or so, I start to warm up. It will be really important that my new family is one that is a bit more laid back. One that will give me the time I need to settle in, but does not have a super busy house hold. 

I am up to date on shots, neutered, microchipped, and on heartworm prevention.

My Adoption Fee is $200.00

With the typical energy of a 6 month old puppy, I love to play, chew bones, and I go crazy for the squeak toys! I am super treat/food motivated which is great for training!
